One of the most common units used to measure time is the second, which is defined as the duration of 9,192,631,770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the caesium-133 atom.

A minute, on the other hand, is a unit of time that is equal to 60 seconds. This means that one minute is equal to 60 times the duration of one second.

To understand how long a minute feels like, it is essential to understand that our perception of time is subjective and can be influenced by various factors such as attention, emotion, and context. For example, when we are engaged in a pleasant activity, time may seem to pass quickly, while time may seem to drag on when we are bored or anxious.

In terms of objective time, a minute can be used to measure a variety of events. For example, it takes approximately one minute for the Earth to rotate by one degree around its axis. It also takes approximately one minute for light to travel from the Moon to the Earth.

In scientific experiments, researchers often use precise measurements of time to study phenomena such as chemical reactions, particle decay, and radioactive decay. For example, if a radioactive sample has a half-life of one minute, this means that half of the sample will decay in one minute, and the other half will remain.

In summary, a minute is a unit of time that is equal to 60 seconds, and the duration of one second is defined as the duration of 9,192,631,770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the caesium-133 atom.
